{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"da1b61c5-a7e5-4d97-a24c-fb3a57c22888","content":"Since you want properties set consistently, use a shared `Directory.Build.props` at the solution root instead of editing each `.csproj`.\n\n**1. Create/update `Directory.Build.props`** at the solution root:\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.0\" />\n  </ItemGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**2. Clean up each `.csproj`** — remove any per-project `<OutputType>` set to `Library` (the default for test projects under VSTest), since the `Directory.Build.props` now sets it to `Exe`.\n\n**3. Update the CI command:**\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\n`--logger trx` is a VSTest concept. With Microsoft.Testing.Platform, TRX reporting is provided by the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package and enabled via `--report-trx`, passed after `--` so `dotnet test` forwards it to the MTP runner.\n\n**Why each change matters:**\n\n| Change | Reason |\n|---|---|\n| `EnableMSTestRunner` | Activates the MTP runner built into MSTest 3.8.0 |\n| `OutputType Exe` | MTP requires each test project to be a self-contained executable |\n| `TrxReport` package | TRX output is a separate extension in MTP (not built-in like VSTest) |\n| `-- --report-trx` | MTP's flag replaces VSTest's `--logger trx` |\n\nTRX files will be written to the test results directory as before. If you need to control the output path, use `--report-trx-filename <path>`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ebd8a54d-ba8b-47d8-9c32-a91c948bda49","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate 3 MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). They're on .NET 8 SDK and use `dotnet test --logger trx` in CI.\n\nLet me provide a concise, accurate answer based on my knowledge of MSTest 3.8.0 and Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Project-level**: Enable MTP by setting `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` in each test project (or a shared `Directory.Build.props`).\n\n\n2. **For consistent properties across all projects**: Use a `Directory.Build.props` file to avoid repetition.\n3. **TRX logger**: With MTP, you'll need to add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` NuGet package to generate TRX reports instead of relying on the VSTest logger.\n4. **CI command changes**: The `dotnet test` command syntax changes with MTP—you'll need to update how the TRX logger is specified in your CI pipeline.\n\nMSTest 3.8.0 has built-in support for Microsoft.Testing.Platform, so you just need to enable the runner and add the TRX extension package.\n\nWith .NET 8 and MTP enabled, `dotnet test` still works but invokes the test app as a self-contained executable rather than through VSTest, and you'll use `--report-trx` instead of `--logger trx` to generate reports. I need to clarify the setup for MSTest 3.8.0 on .NET 8 specifically. I'm setting up a Directory.Build.props file to enable the MSTest runner and mark the project as an executable, plus adding the TRX reporting extension for test result output. The key thing is that `dotnet test` in .NET 8 still routes through VSTest's compatibility layer, so the standard `--logger trx` flag won't work directly—instead I need to pass the option through to the native runner using `-- --report-trx`.\n\nActually, I should reconsider whether `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` is even available in .NET 8, since that might be a .NET 9+ feature. For .NET 8 specifically, the approach is simpler: just enable the MSTest runner with `EnableMSTestRunner` and set the output type to executable, then let `dotnet test` handle the VSTest bridge communication.\n\nFor TRX reporting, I need to add the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package and use the `--report-trx` argument passed through the MTP protocol after the `--` separator in the command line. I can set this up consistently across projects using a Directory.Build.props file that configures both the runner and the reporting extension, then run `dotnet test -- --report-trx` in CI. I'll focus on giving them a straightforward answer with the right package versions and configuration approach rather than getting caught up in the compatibility details.","outputTokens":2036,"requestId":"0832:204131:8597E92:93BFEB5:69EABD75"},"id":"3a27cb23-2486-488c-b8a3-7d24c6ecaa83","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:47:25.891Z","parentId":"50bf452c-3de1-4bbc-99c8-d0536f834c63"}
